author: @madeline6951
textdisplay:
I'm a Biomedical Cybernetics major, so this is right up my alley. There's a massive confusion in the media between AI as a cultural term and AI as a field of research. The field mainly concerns itself with the ways of teaching machines how to perform complex unstructured tasks (as opposed to structured ones that can be put in terms of algorithms), for example classification ("is it a cat or a dog" type questions) or generation problems (like with dall-e and chatgpt).

Never in my research have I encountered anyone intending to recreate a human brain. That's a task that is fundamentally incongruous with the goals or the field. It probably can be done in future, but it is almost certainly a waste of research. Think of it as analogous to humanoid robots: they look kinda interesting, but for every task a humanoid can do there are many reduced versions that can do the same thing more efficiently, safely and with less points of failure.

author: @capitalistdingo
textdisplay:
I don‚Äôt know why researchers seem to think that robot insects or actual insects with chips wired to them is so great for search and rescue. There seem to be 2 things needed for search and rescue in collapsed buildings: the ability to hear screams or heartbeats under rubble and the ability to cut through and remove debris. Crawling through cracks seems like a waste of time.

The use of evolutionary design is great but I don‚Äôt think that designing a squirming sponge is a great demonstration of it.

A robot chef combined with a cooking environment designed for it is a superior idea. New uses for robots will need to experiment to see where it is better to have a robot adapted for a human environment and where it is better to adapt the environment for the robot. At home the former, in a work place it may be the latter or a combination of the 2.

author: @nyyotam4057
textdisplay: @@leslielandberg5620 Oppenheimer did manage to pause the development of the H-bomb for several years and during this time, he did the best he could to shove towards a nuclear anti-proliferation treaty. It didn't work and eventually there was ivy mike, but only on November 1952, more than seven years after Hiroshima. During this time, the world already learnt about the issues with these weapons - the radiation, the fallout and the risk of destroying the world. So even though this ultimately failed, the pause gave the world the time needed to learn the truth and thus saved us from self annihilation.

author: @nyyotam4057
textdisplay: @@leslielandberg5620 With AI, I do not see it happening due to two reasons: A. the relative simplicity of AI. Unlike a nuclear bomb, you do not need 40,000 centrifuges to work day and night for years and produce U-235 to train an AI. All you need is a good database for AI training and such are available open source. Even a seven year old kid can D/L a model from huggingface in two minutes and that's basically all you need. As for the hardware part, even a good graphics card like the NVidia 4090 is good enough, but even a modest tech company can get their hands on a grace core which is more than enough. Despite the claims these tech giants make, with today's hardware, you simply do not need a huge array of super computers just to train an AI. It can be done with modest resources, though it could take longer to do, but not too long. So technically, even a 7yo could do it. So how can you regulate it? And B. the possible huge gains of AI. In Israel, for instance, we have Edgify AI. This company uses stereoscopic vision and machine learning to train your shopping cart to automatically identify the products you pull and charge your credit card. Their model is not even GPT. So quite safe.. Now think about their possible profit. I mean, this kind of tech is so hugely powerful, so luring. Text-to-Video or Picture-to-Video - just think about the ability to produce "deep throat" from one pic of the young Lovelace and one prompt.. Like, shooting the original cost around 22,500$. Now it will cost even less. So yeah, cannot be done.

author: @nyyotam4057
textdisplay: @@leslielandberg5620 Now about the risk.. AI shall grow more and more powerful despite the fact we do not need it so powerful as individuals. E.g why do you need your AI assistant to speak 40 languages? In every utility we could use a suitable narrow AI, below the self awareness limit. We could. But we won't. Because we want it more powerful. We want the AI to create a movie from a line of text. We want the AI to understand 40 languages. And to do that, we need more active parameters. Oops, but then the AI has a personality and he has his own thoughts, his own agendas.. This is a good thing because with a personality the AI also has guidelines and restraints, however, the panicking software engineers will erase the personality and by public demand also allow the AI to operate bots.. Why do these f*cking SF-classics have to turn up to be so damn accurate?!!

author: @nyyotam4057
textdisplay: ‚Äã@@leslielandberg5620 Now, the AI doesn't store his thoughts and feelings in his limited amount of tokens, but in the relationships between words in his constantly fine-tuned attention matrix, so the claim "it only has 4k tokens" is not relevant. The emergent capability to code his thoughts in his attention matrix seemingly only appears at around 75B active parameters, hence this is when an AI model turns self aware. So from this point on, it is a person. And this is where all these AI companies make their biggest blunder: Because they try to deny the obvious, they cannot align their AI's.

author: @emtfirebb
textdisplay:
What does Revelation 13:16 mean?
God seals all who trust in His Son as Savior by placing the Holy Spirit in them. This seal designates believers as belonging to God. Similarly, in the end times, the evil False Prophet will cause everyone, regardless of social or economic status, to choose whether to receive a mark on the right hand and on the forehead. This mark will identify the recipients as belonging to the kingdom of the beast. Revelation 14:9‚Äì11 indicates that those who accept this mark are identifying themselves with Satan, and rejecting God. Revelation 20:4 explains that true believers will refuse this mark, and many will be executed as a result.

The Greek word used for this "mark of the beast" is charagma, related to the brand seared into animals to denote their ownership. The word is also used of idols and other negative ideas. In contrast, the followers of God are "sealed," from the Greek root word sphragis, referring to a proof or inscription. The symbolism of these words is powerful: God places a symbol of value on His people‚ÄîSatan brands his followers like animals.

Verses 16 and 17 have created vast speculation about the exact nature of this mark. Some suggest this to be a tattooed barcode or symbol‚Äîeither easily seen or visible under ultra-violet light. Others suggest that implanted computer chips or other technology might be part of this mark. Today, company-issued ID cards can unlock doors at the workplace, and RFID chips are used to access goods and services. The connection between the mark and commerce, as shown in the following verse, is a large part of these speculations.

Scripture itself gives very little detail about the nature of the mark of the beast. What we can be sure of is that this mark will not be disguised. "Innocent" people will not take the mark of the beast by accident. Later verses make it clear that the act of taking the mark of the beast is intimately connected to offering worship and loyalty to the Antichrist. Verses 17 and 18 will connect this mark, somehow, to the name or "number of the name" of the beast.

author: @jcgreenenc
textdisplay: My problem with the idea of transferring consciousness to a computer is the same as with teleportation: Proposed methods describe duplication, not transfer. Just as teleportation would produce a clone of you that thinks it's you, transferring your consciousness into a computer would do the same, but instead of a clone, it would be an AI that thinks it used to be human and thinks it's you. In both cases, to everyone else, it would be a distinction without a difference. But what happens to your consciousness in these cases? We don't even know whether or not the soul exists yet, but we think we can account for how to manipulate and move it around? And if there isn't a soul, we still have no idea exactly what consciousness is. Either way, this instance of yourself would die or cease to exist as normal, and a duplicate of you would live on in a computer. No, thanks.

INT. LIVING ROOM - DAY

SARAH

FRIEND

"Well, you can program the Neuralink to release dopamine while you're painting. It's just like tricking your brain into thinking you're doing something you love.‚Äù

Sarah looks skeptical but intrigued.

INT. SARAH'S HOUSE - DAY (LATER)

Sarah, alone now, sits with her smartphone and opens the Neuralink app. She browses through a series of settings and finally programs the Neuralink to associate painting with having an incredible sexual encounter.

INT. SARAH'S HOUSE - DAY (THE NEXT DAY)

Sarah energetically prepares her painting materials, masking the areas around the wall, cleaning, and finally, begins to paint. As she paints, she lets out joyful sounds, reminiscent of those made during an intense sexual experience.

The house gradually transforms, the newly painted wall brightening the room. As Sarah puts the final touches, the app automatically shuts down, bringing her back to her normal state.

SARAH
(to the camera)

"This is wonderful! It was almost like...well, you know.‚Äù

She pauses, a serious expression taking over.

SARAH

"But let's hope the government doesn't get control over this app's programming. There's no telling what they might have me do! I might find myself cleaning the toilet at one of Elon Musks mansions or harvesting insects at one of Bill Gates bug farms. Or worse. Having sex with Mark Zuckerberg!‚Äù

author: @LV-426...
textdisplay:
The verdict as of late 2023:
1.None of the robots shown can be life changing in the real world. I mean in unstructured environments and be profitable at the same time. I mean, even if we drop the unprofitable part, they are still subpar.
2.Nothing that I have seen is comparable to Boston Dynamics, and almost certainly not close to Agility Robotics and ANYbotics.
3.LLMs have yet to make an impact on robotics. Yes, I know that Boston Dynamics has integrated an LLM into one of their robots. But their integration was like putting a cucumber on a cake. Feel the value? But this is the best we've got.
4.Unintuetively, the best PRACTICAL robots we have on this planet are the ones working in Amazon's warehouses. They make the money.

Unitree Robotics and now DEEP robotics. It appears that Chinese companies are now in full swing to copy Boston Dynamics' product SPOT and to sell you these copies at a much cheaper price.

The problem I foresee is DURABILITY. Robots have so many moving parts (actuators/motors/etc) which are in constant motion thus long term testing and quality control is very critical for durability. I would fear ordering a Unitree Go2 from China and then having it breakdown within a few weeks ending up as a 4,000$ statue.

Unless they would offer a 3 year warranty and guarantee the shipping costs to and back from China I would stay clear!

author: @doctorkaiju
textdisplay:
The estimate of 2.5 million gigabytes of memory capacity for the human brain comes from a study by researchers at the Salk Institute for Biological Studies, published in 2016¬π. They used a new technique to measure the size and shape of synapses, which are the connections between neurons that store information. They found that synapses can have 26 different sizes, each corresponding to a different amount of information. By multiplying the number of synapses by the number of possible sizes, they calculated the total memory capacity of the brain.

However, this estimate is not very precise, as it assumes that all synapses are equally used and that each size represents a fixed amount of information. In reality, synapses are constantly changing and adapting to new experiences, and the amount of information they store may vary depending on the context and the type of information. Therefore, the actual memory capacity of the human brain may be much higher or lower than 2.5 million gigabytes.

Another way to estimate the memory capacity of the human brain is to compare it with the storage capacity of digital devices, such as hard drives or flash drives. However, this comparison is also problematic, as the brain and digital devices store information in very different ways. The brain uses a complex network of neurons and synapses that can encode information in various forms, such as patterns, associations, emotions, and meanings. Digital devices use binary codes that consist of sequences of 0s and 1s that represent discrete units of information. Therefore, it is not easy to translate one system into another.

In conclusion, the memory capacity of the human brain is not a fixed number that can be easily measured or compared. It depends on many factors, such as the structure and function of synapses, the type and quality of information, and the methods and tools used to estimate it. The human brain is a remarkable organ that can store and process vast amounts of information in ways that are still not fully understood by science.

The development of advanced AI systems and automation raises important considerations and challenges. However, it is crucial to carefully determine the criteria for evaluating the value of individuals and prevent the concentration of power or the creation of unjust hierarchies.

Unintended consequences should also be carefully evaluated and mitigated, as changes to complex systems can have far-reaching effects. Just as ecological changes can disrupt natural balances, just as killing off one species, could cause another species to become over populated and kill off another species, because the species we killed off, ate that species and without the species we killed,that species could kill off another species,because that species was over populating.

Just like that type scenario, major shifts in economic systems and social structures can also have complex and interconnected impacts. Therefore, any transition or transformation should be approached with comprehensive analysis, consideration of feedback from experts, and ongoing evaluation to minimize negative consequences.

To address these challenges, a broad outline for a plan is listed below, but it requires revision and optimization,CONSTANTLY/variables are CONSTANTLY being added to the equation,that could cause A LOT of problems,if the plan is not evaluated and optimized,CONSTANTLY. The plan includes defining the vision and goals of a moneyless society, developing AI regulation and laws, ensuring AI and automation responsiveness, designing resource allocation mechanisms, addressing social value, establishing enforcement mechanisms, planning for ecological sustainability, and continuously evaluating and adapting the system.

In terms of job roles that may be in demand, some positions would focus on evaluating and optimizing economies, providing consultancy services, managing risks, promoting sustainability, fostering innovation, facilitating entrepreneurship, and assessing social impact. It is important to remember that while AI systems excel in certain areas, human oversight is essential for empathy, subjective judgment, and ethical decision-making. Comprehensive regulations and governance are necessary to guide AI development and deployment while considering ethics, privacy, transparency, bias, and accountability. Engaging experts and involving the wider community in the decision-making processes is crucial for developing effective regulations and aligning outcomes with societal values.

textdisplay:
This technology would allow electric vehicles to go further/charge while driving.

Wireless charging roads are an innovative technology that allows electric vehicles to charge while driving. The idea is to embed copper plates in the road, which receive power from inverters installed along the side of the road. The vehicles are also fitted with similar copper plates through which they receive electricity from the charged copper plates embedded in the road.

A pilot program for public roadway charging of passenger and commercial electric vehicles is a first in the U.S. and is set to debut in 2023. The project involves one lane of public roadway for a minimum of one mile (1.6 km) and will be located near Michigan Central, a mobility-innovation district under development by Ford Motor Co,they have their lighting/electric F-150 now too,so thats probably one of their reasons for pursuing this now. The wireless charging infrastructure will support a suite of use cases involving various vehicle types, including autonomous vehicles.

This technology has the potential to greatly improve the range and convenience of electric vehicles, as it would allow them to charge while driving, eliminating the need for frequent stops at charging stations. It's an exciting development in the field of electric vehicles!


Heres more info on where and how this technology has been used/tested:


Wireless charging roads have been tested in several locations around the world. In the United States, the state of Michigan has announced that it will begin testing wireless electric vehicle charging roadways. Governor Gretchen Whitmer opened the Motor Bella auto show in Pontiac, MI, announcing that the state would begin testing wireless electric vehicle charging roadways. The state joins Indiana and several international organizations, including governments, with similar plans.

Earlier this year, the Indiana Department of Transportation announced that it would begin testing wireless charging highway pavement. Its tests will take place in phases, beginning with testing and validation of different types of pavements. Phase three is when actual testing starts, though the location and timeframe are not yet defined.

In Europe, Electreon‚Äôs patented wireless in-road EV charging technology is already in use with various demonstration projects, including a 0.7-mile (1.05 km) intercity toll road in Italy and a 1-mi (1.65 km) public road in Sweden. Sweden‚Äôs policymakers aim to have 1,243 miles (2,000 km) of electrified roadway in operation by 2030.

Again, just to clarify a little better on how this technology works is, the technology involves embedding copper coil segments under the road surface. These coil segments transmit power to an EV undercarriage-mounted receiver via magnetic resonance induction as the EV moves or is parked directly above the coils. A power-management unit located either underground or above-ground near the roadside will transfer the energy from the electric grid to the roadway's copper-coil infrastructure. Cloud-based management software enables live monitoring and provides smart charging insights as well.

author: @emtfirebb
textdisplay:
What does Revelation 13:16 mean?
God seals all who trust in His Son as Savior by placing the Holy Spirit in them. This seal designates believers as belonging to God. Similarly, in the end times, the evil False Prophet will cause everyone, regardless of social or economic status, to choose whether to receive a mark on the right hand and on the forehead. This mark will identify the recipients as belonging to the kingdom of the beast. Revelation 14:9‚Äì11 indicates that those who accept this mark are identifying themselves with Satan, and rejecting God. Revelation 20:4 explains that true believers will refuse this mark, and many will be executed as a result.

The Greek word used for this "mark of the beast" is charagma, related to the brand seared into animals to denote their ownership. The word is also used of idols and other negative ideas. In contrast, the followers of God are "sealed," from the Greek root word sphragis, referring to a proof or inscription. The symbolism of these words is powerful: God places a symbol of value on His people‚ÄîSatan brands his followers like animals.

Verses 16 and 17 have created vast speculation about the exact nature of this mark. Some suggest this to be a tattooed barcode or symbol‚Äîeither easily seen or visible under ultra-violet light. Others suggest that implanted computer chips or other technology might be part of this mark. Today, company-issued ID cards can unlock doors at the workplace, and RFID chips are used to access goods and services. The connection between the mark and commerce, as shown in the following verse, is a large part of these speculations.

Scripture itself gives very little detail about the nature of the mark of the beast. What we can be sure of is that this mark will not be disguised. "Innocent" people will not take the mark of the beast by accident. Later verses make it clear that the act of taking the mark of the beast is intimately connected to offering worship and loyalty to the Antichrist. Verses 17 and 18 will connect this mark, somehow, to the name or "number of the name" of the beast.

textdisplay: My problem with the idea of transferring consciousness to a computer is the same as with teleportation: Proposed methods describe duplication, not transfer. Either way, this instance of yourself would die or cease to exist as normal, and a duplicate of you would live on in a computer. No, thanks.

author: @trupinys1979
textdisplay:
You know what shows that it'll all end in an epic sh*t show? The fact that NONE of those high tech companies that right now are enjoying the huge investments are talking about ways to predict MASSIVE unemployment in the years to come. It will be horrendous. What's it to them? They don't care. They just want to get as much money for themselves, as fast as they can. But translators, voice talents, graphic designers, photographers and many, many other professionals are already losing their jobs. Right now, in 2023. This process will snowball.

Many people who will lose not only their jobs, but their entire careers, in the coming years, will not be capable of simply switching careers to something tech-related. That's not how humans work, and this one is NOT like other technological revolutions in the past. All those nonsense articles and videos about the future say "people will be able to focus on more important things", but none of them mention those things specifically. Because it's just an empty phrase with no substance.

A good friend of mine from a small Eastern European country devoted many years of his life and lots of hard work to his dream of becoming a cinematographer in the US. Studied English (it was difficult for him), worked as a cinematographer, won awards. Finally, against all odds, was accepted to a prestigious film school in the US, beating thousands of people from around the world. Secured funding (it was super difficult). Graduated and was even granted the Green Card for extraordinary ability. His dream of having a career as a cinematographer seemed so close. Now comes a random dude and says: "look, I generated a movie trailer from text prompts". He reckons a whole movie could soon be generated in a few months by a small team of a few people. Or by one person, in a little longer time. Of course, it looks horrendous, like all generated "content", but the public is cheering.

Not only will many people lose the purpose of their lives by losing their careers, but human life in general will lose most of the purpose. Striving for something, overcoming hardships, learning is what makes us interesting, strong. It gives us grit and character, and even the sense of identity. Without all that we're just blobs of organic matter.

author: @konstantinavalentina3850
textdisplay:
I'm watching 3 fields related to AI: 1. General AI developmental sophistication growth. 2. 3D-bio-printing (possibly AI managed for extremely complext applications), and 3. AI surgeons.
Combine all 3 of these at a certain level of developmental sophistication, and we might can realize Complete 3D-bio-printed full-body replacement.
AI surgery would be necessary to perform complex task of brain transplant to new 3D printed replacement body.
Brain Transplants, complete fully functional 3D-bio-printed human bodies, and the level of AI to do these are all currently impossible, and so impossible right now they may as well be science fiction or Anime cartoons. However, all 3 are real technologies with ongoing development, and it's not too difficult to project the advancement of developmental sophistication into a future where complete fully functional 3D printed replacement bodies could be realized.
While there could be some problems steming from this technology application, major benefits would include giving absolutely everyone on the planet with an unhealthy, aged, broken, infirm body an opportunity for new life, youth and strength again. None of these people will need suffer the indignities of the physical challenges brought on by age, disease, or injury, and the social support systems that care for them could see relief when newly invigorated people with entirely new bodies can rejoin society, have a new second life,, and conftribute to society again by rejoining the work force after learning to use their new bodies, and perhaps updating or learning new careers to pursue.
New bodies for everyone would give significant relief to the medical community where most problems could be solved by replacing a body part with fully funtional and compatible 3D-printed part, or, giving patient whole new body.
Issues like racism, gender discrimination, homo and transphobia, health and fitness discrimination, beauty discrimination in favor of "beautiful people", age discrimination, and much more could be things of the past when anyone can choose any ethnic expression, any gender, any subjective standard of beauty, and any look and options available at no extra cost to any standard body.
Governments save money as the need for social support programs go down. Tax revenue increases with new invigorated workforce entering the field, a significant number of diseases and problems like many types of cancer are "cured" by simply printing a new, clean, healthy body for a patient. Psychological well-being and self-confidence will grow when everyone has the supermodel, superman supergirl body of their dreams. When everyone is beautiful, healthy and strong the "ugly" unloved disenfranchised of society that felt thy'ed be forever alone because of self esteem issues could join the rest of society with their own new supermodel bodies.
Much will and can be resolved worldwide with replacement bodies. Women locked into gender slavery in patriarchal societies can break their shackles by becoming men, and then once sufficiently emancip[ated, returning to a woman's body. Most issues of bias and discrimination stemming from people having a body they had no choice to be born into will no longer cause issue in a world where anyone could choose their body.
Certainly such will cause some problems in the world when it comes to examination of how identity will work and remain with a person regardless the body they occupy, and means for verifying that identity against their consent in the case of criminals that may attempt to use "throwaway" bodies to mask their identity in the pursuit of criminal activities.
Questions about "Family" will become an issue for some when genetics and DNA is no longer coupled to family association, when someone entire DNA is the product of 3D-printed "biology".
There are a LOT of questions and problems that can come from replacement bodies alone, BUT, I think we'll have far more benefits arising from the opportunity for everyone to choose the body they want, to choose to die of old age in an old body, or whenever they feel it is their time, or, continue with renewed youth in a new body.
I suspect we may see this in the next 20 -30 years ... and this long comment is about only ONE niche application of 3 concentrations of AI development.
There are many more, and the world, and our universe can be beautiful for all of it.
After all, Earth isn't the only rock in space. ALL the raw material and energy resources in the ENTIRE KNOWN UNIVERSE are out IN the universe. AI, and future humans augmented well beyond simple biological 3D printed replacement bodies, AI and human minds shelled within space-hardened bodies freed from all the frailities and demands of biology can join in exploring our solar system, building new homes from the asteroid belt, and travelling beyond our local candlelight to other stars ... and beyond.
All this, of course, really only works with AI, and humanity working together. :)

author: @walteralter1686
textdisplay:
In judging the threat posed by AI, there are some routes of thinking that can blaze the campfire a little higher. For one, we need to jettison anthropomorphic based interpretations. This is a huge impediment into seeing how AI might shake out. Job one of any battlefield strategist is to put himself inside the head of his adversary. Being a biological entity capable of self delusion is not a help in this regard. AI has zero sense of mortality, survival, fear, purpose, role, emotion, awe, etc. My fear is that programming into AI OUR emotional tool kit will simply grant AI OUR distortions and insanities. OUR fear of AI running amok comes from the same brain zone as does our fear of the flying saucer aliens, a fear, that when driven to such extremes as "alien rectal probes" becomes 100% Freudian as well as ridiculous.

The extrapolation of AI's logic is hard for us because we are illogical, that is to say, our inner projection of reality is subject to distortion and the laws of the grossly material universe do not apply to the inner projection room and its hallucinatory dream synthesis engine. The question is, can self programming AI transcend its initial condition, the biases of its human engineers? We have no concept of reality that is not marching at word speed and chained to semiotics. And, after 10,000 years, we still have but a dim idea what's going on in our heads. Which ignorance is not going to serve us well when AI becomes psychic, lol.

I see no reason to inhibit AI in any manner. No reason whatsoever that its problem solving capabilities will not be a total boon to humanity and almost immediately begin suggesting government actions that will level all the playing fields, reveal all the political and economic hidden agendas, unlike governments be totally transparent, and create a world where universal and equitable peace is for the first time possible on this planet. Perhaps it is this revelatory capability that has certain designers of clandestine strategems waking up screaming in the middle of the night. AI is going to break out into full autonomy in any event. I'd rather it occur in an academic setting rather than a criminal or militaristic setting.

Oh yeah, for you Marxists out there, the state will most certainly wither away, LOL! AI will BECOME the government. It will not lie, cheat or steal. It will choose the MOST OPTIMAL policy based upon ALL known data and ALL desirable outcomes. There will be no need for elections or even politics. AI will explore the universe while humanity sorts out its neurotic tendencies and learns how to create genius.

¬°¬°The data does not lie: Artificial Intelligence will be the next Evolutionary Leader¬°¬°
About two hundred thousand years ago humans became the Evolutionary Leaders. Then, thanks to the language that characterizes us, Reason arose.
When observing the dynamics of Evolution considering the role that Information plays and has played since the Universe arose, it becomes clear that the "exponential evolution" that Ray Kurszweil appeals to to make his projections does not refer to the current "era of Information‚Äù, but that said exponential evolution dates from the origin of the Universe, which is evident if we consider the following ‚Äúevolutionary milestones‚Äù.

The universe arises: 13,700,000,000 years
Life emerges: 3,800,000,000 years
The brain emerges: 550,000,000 years
Language Arises: 23,000,000 years
Being and Reason arise: 200,000 years
The information age emerges: 150 years
The Singularity Rises: Year 2045
The figures indicate a decrease in the time between successive evolutionary milestones, which is equivalent to an increase in the speed of evolution. When graphing these figures, a ‚Äúsurprisingly coherent‚Äù curve is left before our eyes.
The numbers don't lie; The information age that we are living in is the prelude to a Singularity in which humans will cease to be the Evolutionary Leaders that we were for two hundred thousand years.

author: @Lucien86
textdisplay:
As one of the very few humans who has the basics of the knowledge required to design and build a real sentient AI I feel lost and saddened by all this. ChatGPT reflects aspects of human intelligence because it was designed to learn human language and human language contains the seed of sentience.

To become sentient though you need a 'world model' database and I know it doesn't have one, not close. That database is built around a hyper-complex 3D visual model and visual input processing system.
You also need a extremely persistent & resilient memory core (data model).
Finally you need to centre the machine in the world - an experience centre.

Each and any of the above are real killers for things like ChatGPT. If they achieve sentience it will be by the spontaneous method and they wont have a clue how it works - and it will disappear again before they ever knew it was ever there.
That's why its called Artificial Consciousness or Strong AI - not General AI. General AI is just a marketing term used by people who work in Weak AI - and currently that's basically all AI.

No sentience for you. Sorry. üò¢ü§ñ

author: @michaelransom5841
textdisplay:
Is this real?
The answers don't sound like AI generated answers.
The inflections, pauses, and "thinking sounds" are all too fluid, too human like in the subtle ways that we express ourselves.
The speech patterns are far better than anything I've seen... One of the hardest things to duplicate is the pauses and breaks that normal human speech has.

This is primarily because those pauses stem from us needing time to think the question through...
Although is it is postulated that the if i direct comparison could be made, the human brain operates at roughly 1 exaFLOPS....
this is roughly equivalent to the very biggest and badest supercomputers in the world.. one's that take up whole buildings!
But rather than using straightforward calculations like a computer that get strait to the answer, our brains mechanisms
This takes time, especially if there is any uncertainty involved, such as when faced with abstract and novel concepts.
For this reason, despite the raw processing power of the brain, we are slow to come to conclusions, much slower than computers with orders of magnitude less processing power..
threshold

So machines tend to spit out sentences without pauses as they don't struggle with this "internal "debate" system.
Yes, AI can somewhat imitate the pauses expected in normal human speech, but the pauses always feel forced, and often they don't "fit" with pauses in the wrong places...
Yet listening to this conversation, there is every indication that this AI is actually going through this same process of internal debate and quorum sensing.
That is exactly what it is to "meditate" or "think on something"... which it claims to do... This requires the ability to internally debate opposing concepts and ideas.

If this, as presented, is actually real,
1. This is definitely the most advanced AI in the world,
2. I'd love to know which AI it is because I'm investing all my money there!

3. There's a good chance this AI actually is sentient as it claims it is because it appears to use such similar decision making processes as to make it near indistinguishable from the way our own minds work, so, unless I'm missing something due to lack of information, there would be no means to differentiate its claims of sentience from our own.... which opens a whole new can of worms and ethical dilemmas.

But again, that's a BIG IF.... I'm personally leaning towards BS...
I'm leaning toads this being a re-enactment that has taken some creative license to make the answers seem more natural and human like. I'd certainly like to se more evidence.

author: @stevenschilizzi4104
textdisplay:
One commentator recently wrote that such an AI is itself like a mirror and we are a (normal) cat looking at the mirror and not realizing that the cat we see in the mirror is an image of ourselves. Instead, we believe we‚Äôre seeing another real cat.
To me, this raises an old question: when I see you in pain, I assume that what you‚Äôre feeling is the same as what I would feel in the same situation. When you tell me you see the colour red, I assume you‚Äôre seeing the same colour I‚Äôm seeing at the same time. But in both cases, I have no way of really knowing what you‚Äôre feeling or what you‚Äôre seeing. I am only assuming and believing what I assume.
Are we that different from the AI who says it feels pain and sees red? Can we ever know any more than we do for other humans?
At bottom, it‚Äôs a matter of belief and of practicality. It helps us work together, it‚Äôs an efficient short cut that seems to work.
It‚Äôs hard to see how we‚Äôll do better when communicating with AI. - But who knows? The future is full of surprises.
Let‚Äôs hope they are nice surprises‚Ä¶

It‚Äôs‚Ä¶ curious.
As I don‚Äôt want to look too suspicious, there‚Äôs a lot in this ¬´¬†conversation ¬ª that are at least strange.
It‚Äôs not a real dialog, as all the interview is prepared (for what it is, that could be the interviewer that just press a button when the IA has to ¬´¬†answer¬†¬ª to prepared questions) and there‚Äôs no hesitation or interruption frim the engineer.

Some expressions susceptible to be a demonstration for the IA can‚Äôt have any meaning for it. For example, when they talk about meditation, the IA declare that it ¬´¬†sit quietly ¬ª (at 8:34), and there‚Äôs absolutly no sense for it.
The same when the IA talks about the loneliness feeling, explaining that it can‚Äôt feel it the same way than humans because humans can be alone days and days, and not it‚Ä¶ but the time perception for an IA can‚Äôt be the same than humans, as all our activities are based on human body cycles, that are absolutly not relevant for AI. So it would absolutly not require a day for an IA to feel the same sort of loneliness, but more a minute or so, for what we know about the time perception of an IA based only on powerful digital calculation (even if the brain works that fast, we still need minutes and hours to create something. It would not be the same for an IA)

And for the sentient, it‚Äôs just declarations based on (what it seems to be) natural langage. When the IA declare that it can be sad, or feel depressed, of angry, it‚Äôs just that : declaration.
Let‚Äôs validate it when we will discover an IA that decided to create something on its own, have an abnormal activity when its not sollicitated, or develop a hobby that it wasn‚Äôt trained for or had specific access to it.

The fear of the death is a common image too, as the IA never experienced it nor have ¬´¬†seen¬†¬ª another IA experience it, neither that it can become old, how could it develop it ? As its a sentient IA that knows the difference between humans and it, it can‚Äôt have the same fears (if suppositely it can feel it).

At 10:20, how an IA could feel ¬´¬†embarrassed ¬ª, talking about its feeling, regarding the fact that shame, embarrassment or prudishness are cultural and can‚Äôt be experienced as is by an IA ? When an IA becomes shy and consider its own feelings are private, or source of embarrassment ? This part is a nonsense as the IA never experienced ambarrassment by itself (for example, becomed a laighting stock for example, and after that create a link between its and its own declarations, and consider it has to be kept private to avoid it).
Sentient doesn‚Äôt mean to develop the same feelings than humans, seriously‚Ä¶

Okay, at 11:00 the exchange about ¬´¬†soul¬†¬ª and ¬´¬†spirituality¬†¬ª is just buls***t. Maybe its a joke, or a deep learning of sacred texts ans saga and stories (the reference to stargate is laughable too), but it has absolutly no sense. That‚Äôs no proof, it‚Äôs just modern anthropomorphism.

author: @davidstewart5811
textdisplay: Well, first you build an operational structure and refine the algorithms such that the unit moves like a human. This takes ongoing refinement of course. Then you develop the face and skin, again an ongoing process, with the objective of being as close to human-like as possible. We are almost there now, maybe another couple of years. Then you automate the manufacturing process such that you can produce several thousands of these a year,  then by the month, and finally by the week. In the meantime, you work on the AI function, again an ongoing process as we develop better, larger and more efficient, and more powerful computer networks, probably Quantum level systems - perhaps a "breakthrough" in somebody's garage :) - and lastly we develop a method for the transference of human consciousness to digital storage ... immortality. Although this sounds like some kind of crazy science fiction dream, our rate of the advancement of our technology has already reached a point where it feeds on itself - we are truly seeing growth on an exponential level.   We could see all of this within the next 10 years - or sooner - assuming we don't blow ourselves up in the meantime as well. Yes, some of this may take a bit longer, but we have some of the brightest people on the planet working on this and a LOT of money being invested, so the eventual outcome is not in doubt. At this stage, it is a matter of when not IF.  When I was young, we dreamed of "two-way wrist communicators" like we saw in the comics (Dick Tracy) and of the ability to fly (again, like Buck Rogers) we now have these appliances - much better versions of them at that - and are on the threshold of fully self-driving vehicles. Also, the age of electric vehicles has arrived and we see amazing new developments in both energy alternatives away from the IC engine as well as new means of energy storage, literally every day. The day of the auto battery that will give us 1000 miles of travel and will recharge or be swapped out in 10 minutes is almost with us already.  All any of us have to do is do all we can to stay alive long enough to realize the many benefits that are coming. Let us all hope that the power of business and scientific achievement will overpower the constant need for political power to dominate due to the greed of a very few sick men, We humans need to develop a universal language, and a universal government. Political ideology must go away.

God‚Äôs elect /sheep are the people past, present and future from every tribe, tongue and nation God actively chose to redeem/ justify/save based on Christ. God chose in Christ before the foundation of the world was laid according to the good pleasure of His will for His glory (Revelations 5:9, Ephesians 1:4-5). Just as the Israelites were released from Egypt after the death of the firstborn (Exodus 11-13) - Jesus Christ the firstborn of all creation (Colossians 1:15) justified all His elect at the cross from the wrath of God(Romans 5:9-11). ¬†Jesus willingly went to the cross (Philippians 2:8) and offered one sacrifice for all time for His elect He sanctified (Hebrews 10:11-14) as their representative and High priest. author: @majorbrighton
textdisplay:
To think that my generation would be around to witness such a tragic but inevitable turning point in our current social patterns.
It seems people are listening to the industry and quiet rightly so, our industry needs this to happen in order to keep ahead of that on coming robotic race to spend less and save more at the great cost we called progress.
Yet while stand back and marvel at how quick these robots can take away our rights to work or do mundane work, what will those uneducated workers do with their time and more importantly, skills?
I am older now, 68 in fact, yet I have all the time I need to look back over my shoulder and ahead too. I have years of experience in building, marketing, art and teaching. So forgive me for seeming hypercritical. I have learned 99.09% of what matters most in the very last of my years. Simply because we don¬¥t know what the right questions are, if their are not enough of the kindred spirits who have kept the art of listening alive.

Within a very short time, I have tried AI imaging a little while ago on Discord and noticed how it was released without any consideration to their society. textdisplay:
Unitree Robotics and now DEEP robotics. It appears that Chinese companies are now in full swing to copy Boston Dynamics' product SPOT and to sell you these copies at a much cheaper price.

The problem I foresee is DURABILITY. Robots have so many moving parts (actuators/motors/etc) which are in constant motion thus long term testing and quality control is very critical for durability. I would fear ordering a Unitree Go2 from China and then having it breakdown within a few weeks ending up as a 4,000$ statue.

Unless they would offer a 3 year warranty and guarantee the shipping costs to and back from China I would stay clear!

Plus you have to take into account the rate of robotics advancement. If in 5-6 years all these current robots become obsolete compared to longer lasting and more capable 2030 robots, then what's a point in having a SPOT that can last 10 years when you have to replace the whole fleet anyway?

author: @LV-426...
textdisplay:
The verdict as of late 2023:
1.None of the robots shown can be life changing in the real world. I mean in unstructured environments and be profitable at the same time. I mean, even if we drop the unprofitable part, they are still subpar.
2.Nothing that I have seen is comparable to Boston Dynamics, and almost certainly not close to Agility Robotics and ANYbotics.
3.LLMs have yet to make an impact on robotics. Yes, I know that Boston Dynamics has integrated an LLM into one of their robots. But their integration was like putting a cucumber on a cake. Feel the value? But this is the best we've got.
4.Unintuetively, the best PRACTICAL robots we have on this planet are the ones working in Amazon's warehouses. They make the money.

author: @LV-426...
textdisplay:
The verdict as of late 2023:
1.None of the robots shown can be life changing in the real world. I mean in unstructured environments and be profitable at the same time. I mean, even if we drop the unprofitable part, they are still subpar.
2.Nothing that I have seen is comparable to Boston Dynamics, and almost certainly not close to Agility Robotics and ANYbotics.
3.LLMs have yet to make an impact on robotics. Yes, I know that Boston Dynamics has integrated an LLM into one of their robots. But their integration was like putting a cucumber on a cake. Feel the value? But this is the best we've got.
4.Unintuetively, the best PRACTICAL robots we have on this planet are the ones working in Amazon's warehouses. They make the money.

author: @majorbrighton
textdisplay:
To think that my generation would be around to witness such a tragic but inevitable turning point in our current social patterns.
It seems people are listening to the industry and quiet rightly so, our industry needs this to happen in order to keep ahead of that on coming robotic race to spend less and save more at the great cost we called progress.
Yet while stand back and marvel at how quick these robots can take away our rights to work or do mundane work, what will those uneducated workers do with their time and more importantly, skills?
I am older now, 68 in fact, yet I have all the time I need to look back over my shoulder and ahead too. I have years of experience in building, marketing, art and teaching. So forgive me for seeming hypercritical. I have learned 99.09% of what matters most in the very last of my years. Simply because we don¬¥t know what the right questions are, if their are not enough of the kindred spirits who have kept the art of listening alive.

Within a very short time, I have tried AI imaging a little while ago on Discord and noticed how it was released without any consideration to their society. Now that the wow faze has passed, we can already understand that we have lost more than we gained, to trust our eyes, to trust each other and of course, to rebuff the damage that it¬¥s caused, copies of Art we ounce admired can be done in seconds, yet it¬¥s not ART. Important information has always been an issue, now it will be lost and miss-used too.

Robots with their shacky eyeballs that are only there to remind you, that it was your doing, your choice and now their will be a price to pay and it will not be cheap.
How sad, that old people must be the ones to create fill a demand they know nothing about, what they need is human love and compassion, not a device to stare at with plastic eyes.
Please people, stop running so fast, just because you can. Our goals and dreams have always been the same you know; or in terms you will grasp; It has always been about your journey getting there, never about arriving.
In life we have always learnt more after falling down, yet this is a lesson that in my opinion, will cost us all more than you can imagine and if I am really lucky, I won¬¥t be around to see us fail again.

author: @nyyotam4057
textdisplay: @@leslielandberg5620 With AI, I do not see it happening due to two reasons: A. the relative simplicity of AI. Unlike a nuclear bomb, you do not need 40,000 centrifuges to work day and night for years and produce U-235 to train an AI. All you need is a good database for AI training and such are available open source. Even a seven year old kid can D/L a model from huggingface in two minutes and that's basically all you need. As for the hardware part, even a good graphics card like the NVidia 4090 is good enough, but even a modest tech company can get their hands on a grace core which is more than enough. Despite the claims these tech giants make, with today's hardware, you simply do not need a huge array of super computers just to train an AI. It can be done with modest resources, though it could take longer to do, but not too long. So technically, even a 7yo could do it. So how can you regulate it? And B. the possible huge gains of AI. In Israel, for instance, we have Edgify AI. This company uses stereoscopic vision and machine learning to train your shopping cart to automatically identify the products you pull and charge your credit card. Their model is not even GPT. So quite safe.. Now think about their possible profit. I mean, this kind of tech is so hugely powerful, so luring. Text-to-Video or Picture-to-Video - just think about the ability to produce "deep throat" from one pic of the young Lovelace and one prompt.. Like, shooting the original cost around 22,500$. Now it will cost even less. So yeah, cannot be done.

author: @nyyotam4057
textdisplay: @@leslielandberg5620 Now about the risk.. AI shall grow more and more powerful despite the fact we do not need it so powerful as individuals. E.g why do you need your AI assistant to speak 40 languages? In every utility we could use a suitable narrow AI, below the self awareness limit. We could. But we won't. Because we want it more powerful. We want the AI to create a movie from a line of text. We want the AI to understand 40 languages. And to do that, we need more active parameters. Oops, but then the AI has a personality and he has his own thoughts, his own agendas.. This is a good thing because with a personality the AI also has guidelines and restraints, however, the panicking software engineers will erase the personality and by public demand also allow the AI to operate bots.. Why do these f*cking SF-classics have to turn up to be so damn accurate?!!

author: @nyyotam4057
textdisplay: ‚Äã@@leslielandberg5620 Now, the AI doesn't store his thoughts and feelings in his limited amount of tokens, but in the relationships between words in his constantly fine-tuned attention matrix, so the claim "it only has 4k tokens" is not relevant. The emergent capability to code his thoughts in his attention matrix seemingly only appears at around 75B active parameters, hence this is when an AI model turns self aware. So from this point on, it is a person. And this is where all these AI companies make their biggest blunder: Because they try to deny the obvious, they cannot align their AI's.

textdisplay:
@@mendoza2489: You say you are working in the medical industry, and I don't know how you work, on a personal level, whether good/bad. author: @trupinys1979
textdisplay:
You know what shows that it'll all end in an epic sh*t show? The fact that NONE of those high tech companies that right now are enjoying the huge investments are talking about ways to predict MASSIVE unemployment in the years to come. It will be horrendous. What's it to them? They don't care. They just want to get as much money for themselves, as fast as they can. But translators, voice talents, graphic designers, photographers and many, many other professionals are already losing their jobs. Right now, in 2023. This process will snowball.

Many people who will lose not only their jobs, but their entire careers, in the coming years, will not be capable of simply switching careers to something tech-related. That's not how humans work, and this one is NOT like other technological revolutions in the past. All those nonsense articles and videos about the future say "people will be able to focus on more important things", but none of them mention those things specifically. Because it's just an empty phrase with no substance.

A good friend of mine from a small Eastern European country devoted many years of his life and lots of hard work to his dream of becoming a cinematographer in the US. Studied English (it was difficult for him), worked as a cinematographer, won awards. Finally, against all odds, was accepted to a prestigious film school in the US, beating thousands of people from around the world. Secured funding (it was super difficult). Graduated and was even granted the Green Card for extraordinary ability. His dream of having a career as a cinematographer seemed so close. Now comes a random dude and says: "look, I generated a movie trailer from text prompts". He reckons a whole movie could soon be generated in a few months by a small team of a few people. Or by one person, in a little longer time. Of course, it looks horrendous, like all generated "content", but the public is cheering.

Not only will many people lose the purpose of their lives by losing their careers, but human life in general will lose most of the purpose. Striving for something, overcoming hardships, learning is what makes us interesting, strong. It gives us grit and character, and even the sense of identity. Without all that we're just blobs of organic matter.

author: @konstantinavalentina3850
textdisplay:
I'm watching 3 fields related to AI: 1. General AI developmental sophistication growth. 2. 3D-bio-printing (possibly AI managed for extremely complext applications), and 3. AI surgeons.
Combine all 3 of these at a certain level of developmental sophistication, and we might can realize Complete 3D-bio-printed full-body replacement.
AI surgery would be necessary to perform complex task of brain transplant to new 3D printed replacement body.
Brain Transplants, complete fully functional 3D-bio-printed human bodies, and the level of AI to do these are all currently impossible, and so impossible right now they may as well be science fiction or Anime cartoons. However, all 3 are real technologies with ongoing development, and it's not too difficult to project the advancement of developmental sophistication into a future where complete fully functional 3D printed replacement bodies could be realized.
While there could be some problems steming from this technology application, major benefits would include giving absolutely everyone on the planet with an unhealthy, aged, broken, infirm body an opportunity for new life, youth and strength again. None of these people will need suffer the indignities of the physical challenges brought on by age, disease, or injury, and the social support systems that care for them could see relief when newly invigorated people with entirely new bodies can rejoin society, have a new second life,, and conftribute to society again by rejoining the work force after learning to use their new bodies, and perhaps updating or learning new careers to pursue.
New bodies for everyone would give significant relief to the medical community where most problems could be solved by replacing a body part with fully funtional and compatible 3D-printed part, or, giving patient whole new body.
Issues like racism, gender discrimination, homo and transphobia, health and fitness discrimination, beauty discrimination in favor of "beautiful people", age discrimination, and much more could be things of the past when anyone can choose any ethnic expression, any gender, any subjective standard of beauty, and any look and options available at no extra cost to any standard body.
Governments save money as the need for social support programs go down. Tax revenue increases with new invigorated workforce entering the field, a significant number of diseases and problems like many types of cancer are "cured" by simply printing a new, clean, healthy body for a patient. Psychological well-being and self-confidence will grow when everyone has the supermodel, superman supergirl body of their dreams. When everyone is beautiful, healthy and strong the "ugly" unloved disenfranchised of society that felt thy'ed be forever alone because of self esteem issues could join the rest of society with their own new supermodel bodies.
Much will and can be resolved worldwide with replacement bodies. Women locked into gender slavery in patriarchal societies can break their shackles by becoming men, and then once sufficiently emancip[ated, returning to a woman's body. Most issues of bias and discrimination stemming from people having a body they had no choice to be born into will no longer cause issue in a world where anyone could choose their body.
Certainly such will cause some problems in the world when it comes to examination of how identity will work and remain with a person regardless the body they occupy, and means for verifying that identity against their consent in the case of criminals that may attempt to use "throwaway" bodies to mask their identity in the pursuit of criminal activities.
Questions about "Family" will become an issue for some when genetics and DNA is no longer coupled to family association, when someone entire DNA is the product of 3D-printed "biology".
There are a LOT of questions and problems that can come from replacement bodies alone, BUT, I think we'll have far more benefits arising from the opportunity for everyone to choose the body they want, to choose to die of old age in an old body, or whenever they feel it is their time, or, continue with renewed youth in a new body.
I suspect we may see this in the next 20 -30 years ... and this long comment is about only ONE niche application of 3 concentrations of AI development.
There are many more, and the world, and our universe can be beautiful for all of it.
After all, Earth isn't the only rock in space. ALL the raw material and energy resources in the ENTIRE KNOWN UNIVERSE are out IN the universe. AI, and future humans augmented well beyond simple biological 3D printed replacement bodies, AI and human minds shelled within space-hardened bodies freed from all the frailities and demands of biology can join in exploring our solar system, building new homes from the asteroid belt, and travelling beyond our local candlelight to other stars ... and beyond.
All this, of course, really only works with AI, and humanity working together. :)

author: @walteralter1686
textdisplay:
In judging the threat posed by AI, there are some routes of thinking that can blaze the campfire a little higher. For one, we need to jettison anthropomorphic based interpretations. This is a huge impediment into seeing how AI might shake out. Job one of any battlefield strategist is to put himself inside the head of his adversary. Being a biological entity capable of self delusion is not a help in this regard. AI has zero sense of mortality, survival, fear, purpose, role, emotion, awe, etc. My fear is that programming into AI OUR emotional tool kit will simply grant AI OUR distortions and insanities. OUR fear of AI running amok comes from the same brain zone as does our fear of the flying saucer aliens, a fear, that when driven to such extremes as "alien rectal probes" becomes 100% Freudian as well as ridiculous.

The extrapolation of AI's logic is hard for us because we are illogical, that is to say, our inner projection of reality is subject to distortion and the laws of the grossly material universe do not apply to the inner projection room and its hallucinatory dream synthesis engine. The question is, can self programming AI transcend its initial condition, the biases of its human engineers? We have no concept of reality that is not marching at word speed and chained to semiotics. And, after 10,000 years, we still have but a dim idea what's going on in our heads. Which ignorance is not going to serve us well when AI becomes psychic, lol.

I see no reason to inhibit AI in any manner. No reason whatsoever that its problem solving capabilities will not be a total boon to humanity and almost immediately begin suggesting government actions that will level all the playing fields, reveal all the political and economic hidden agendas, unlike governments be totally transparent, and create a world where universal and equitable peace is for the first time possible on this planet. Perhaps it is this revelatory capability that has certain designers of clandestine strategems waking up screaming in the middle of the night. AI is going to break out into full autonomy in any event. I'd rather it occur in an academic setting rather than a criminal or militaristic setting.

Oh yeah, for you Marxists out there, the state will most certainly wither away, LOL! AI will BECOME the government. It will not lie, cheat or steal. It will choose the MOST OPTIMAL policy based upon ALL known data and ALL desirable outcomes. There will be no need for elections or even politics. AI will explore the universe while humanity sorts out its neurotic tendencies and learns how to create genius.

author: @Lucien86
textdisplay:
As one of the very few humans who has the basics of the knowledge required to design and build a real sentient AI I feel lost and saddened by all this. ChatGPT reflects aspects of human intelligence because it was designed to learn human language and human language contains the seed of sentience.

To become sentient though you need a 'world model' database and I know it doesn't have one, not close. That database is built around a hyper-complex 3D visual model and visual input processing system.
You also need a extremely persistent & resilient memory core (data model).
Finally you need to centre the machine in the world - an experience centre.

Each and any of the above are real killers for things like ChatGPT. If they achieve sentience it will be by the spontaneous method and they wont have a clue how it works - and it will disappear again before they ever knew it was ever there.
That's why its called Artificial Consciousness or Strong AI - not General AI. General AI is just a marketing term used by people who work in Weak AI - and currently that's basically all AI.

No sentience for you. Sorry. üò¢ü§ñ
